- $h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34}$ J·s (Planck's constant)
- $c = 3.00 \times 10^8$ m/s (speed of light)
- $\lambda = 300 \times 10^{-9}$ m (wavelength)

$$E = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34})(3.00 \times 10^8)}{300 \times 10^{-9}}$$

$$E = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \text{ J}$$

**Step 2: Calculate energy per mole**

Multiply by Avogadro's number ($N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23}$ mol$^{-1}$):

$$E_{\text{molar}} = (6.626 \times 10^{-19})(6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.99 \times 10^5 \text{ J/mol}$$

**Step 3: Convert to kJ/mol**

$$E_{\text{molar}} = \frac{3.99 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399 \text{ kJ/mol}$$

This is essentially equal to the typical single-bond energy of 400 kJ/mol, which explains why UV photons can break chemical bonds.

